{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491491"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:49:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:49:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"958"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/958"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.03,0.18,0.67,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"958"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81669"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/958"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"958"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66967"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"191"},{"type":"tags","id":"1305"},{"type":"tags","id":"3338"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"837"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1463"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1807"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10724"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42180"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81669"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of loose bowel motions. He reports bulky, pale, oily stools with occasional faecal urgency and incontinence. He has been attending the hospital obesity clinic and was recently commenced on a new weight loss medication. He has no other medical history and takes no other regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His BMI is 55 kg/m2.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications was he most likely to have been recently prescribed?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metformin","Empagliflozin","Semaglutide","Orlistat","Topiramate"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of steatorrhoea (fatty, pale, bulky stools) after starting a weight loss medication. \u003Cstrong\u003EOrlistat\u003C/strong\u003E works by inhibiting pancreatic lipases, preventing the absorption of dietary fat. This mechanism directly causes steatorrhoea in up to 30% of patients. The side effect can be improved by reducing dietary fat intake to less than 30% of total calories.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetformin\u003C/strong\u003E can cause gastrointestinal side effects including diarrhoea, but this typically presents as watery stools rather than steatorrhoea. The diarrhoea is usually dose-dependent and improves with extended-release formulations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E is an SGLT2 inhibitor that increases glycosuria, and subsequently promotes both glycaemic control and weight loss. It is therefore useful in the treatment of patients with type 2 diabetes mellitus (as well as heart failure). However, its adverse effects mainly relate to urinary tract infections/thrush and euglycaemic ketoacidosis rather than steatorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESemaglutide\u003C/strong\u003E and other GLP-1 receptor agonists commonly cause nausea, vomiting and diarrhoea due to delayed gastric emptying. However, they do not interfere with fat absorption and therefore do not cause steatorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopiramate\u003C/strong\u003E can cause taste changes and decreased appetite but is not associated with steatorrhoea. Its main side effects are cognitive (confusion, difficulty concentrating) and sensory (paraesthesias).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll of these medications are approved for weight management, making them plausible options. However, only orlistat\u0027s mechanism of action directly explains the patient\u0027s presenting symptoms of steatorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Reduced absorption of fat-soluble vitamins and steatorrhoea are common side effects of orlistat therapy.","Gastrointestinal side effects are common to many weight loss medications but the pattern differs between drug classes.","Steatorrhoea can be improved by reducing dietary fat intake while taking orlistat."],"references":["Orlistat. In: AMH Online [Internet]. 2021 [cited 31 January 2021]. Available from: https://amhonline-amh-net-au.edu.au/chapters/gastrointestinal-drugs/other-gastrointestinal-drugs/orlistat","Apovian CM, Aronne LJ, Bessesen DH, McDonnell ME, Murad MH, et al. Pharmacological management of obesity: an endocrine Society clinical practice guideline. J Clin Endocrinol Metab. 2015;100(2):342-62. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25590212/","Walmsley R, Sumithran P. Current and emerging medications for the management of obesity in adults. Med J Aust || doi: 10.5694/mja2.51871  Published online: 20 March 2023"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66967"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"958"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66967"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T19:28:12+10:30"